                        <div>
                            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/05/Krishna_and_the_Gopis_frolicking_in_the_River_Yamuna.jpg" alt="Krishna and Gopis in River Yamuna" class="w-full h-auto object-cover aspect-square rounded-lg">
                             <p class="image-caption rounded-b-lg"><strong>Image:</strong> Krishna with the Gopis (cow-herd girls) in the celestial Yamuna river. <br><strong>Author/School:</strong> Rajput painting, c. 1760. <br><strong>Context:</strong> This artwork highlights the playful and joyful nature (*lila*) of the supreme abode, where all interactions are imbued with divine love. <br><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Krishna_and_the_Gopis_frolicking_in_the_River_Yamuna.jpg" target="_blank" class="underline">Wikimedia Commons</a></p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <img src="https://i.pinimg.com/originals/e5/22/a9/e522a945d73674681559d7491799276d.jpg" alt="Modern ISKCON art of Goloka" class="w-full h-auto object-cover aspect-square rounded-lg">
                             <p class="image-caption rounded-b-lg"><strong>Image:</strong> A modern, vibrant depiction of Goloka Vrindavan. <br><strong>Author/School:</strong> An ISKCON (International Society for Krishna Consciousness) artist. <br><strong>Context:</strong> Created for devotional and educational purposes to make the transcendental realm accessible and appealing to a global, contemporary audience. <br><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.pinterest.com/pin/528227399895286576/" target="_blank" class="underline">Pinterest / ISKCON Desire Tree</a></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Vaikuntha & Brahmaloka -->
                 <div class="content-card rounded-lg">
                    <div class="p-6">
                        <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2 text-tertiary-primary">Vaikuntha & Brahmaloka: Realms of Majesty and Creation</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-gray-700">While Goloka is pastoral, Vaikuntha, the abode of Vishnu, is a realm of unimaginable opulence and majesty, with self-illuminated floating palaces of gold and jewels. Brahmaloka, the realm of the creator-god Brahma, is the highest plane within the material universe, a destination for highly advanced yogis and sages who have not yet attained full liberation into the spiritual sky.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="image-gallery grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 p-6 bg-gray-50 rounded-b-lg">
                        <div>
                            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/34/Vishnu_and_Lakshmi_on_Garuda_in_Vaikuntha_loka.jpg" alt="Vishnu and Lakshmi in Vaikuntha" class="w-full h-auto object-cover aspect-square rounded-lg">
                             <p class="image-caption rounded-b-lg"><strong>Image:</strong> Vishnu and his consort Lakshmi seated in Vaikuntha. <br><strong>Author/School:</strong> Contemporary Indian Artist. <br><strong>Context:</strong> This depiction emphasizes the regal and majestic nature of Vaikuntha as a place of divine order, power, and opulence, distinct from Goloka's pastoral sweetness. <br><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Vishnu_and_Lakshmi_on_Garuda_in_Vaikuntha_loka.jpg" target="_blank" class="underline">Wikimedia Commons</a></p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/A_lithograph_of_Sheshashayi_Vishnu_by_Raja_Ravi_Varma.jpg" alt="Sheshashayi Vishnu" class="w-full h-auto object-cover aspect-square rounded-lg">
                             <p class="image-caption rounded-b-lg"><strong>Image:</strong> Sheshashayi Vishnu, reclining on the serpent Ananta Shesha, with Brahma emerging from his navel. <br><strong>Author/School:</strong> Raja Ravi Varma Press, c. 1910. <br><strong>Context:</strong> A classic print that visualizes the cosmic hierarchy, showing Brahma's realm (Brahmaloka) originating from Vishnu's supreme abode (Vaikuntha). <br><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:A_lithograph_of_Sheshashayi_Vishnu_by_Raja_Ravi_Varma.jpg" target="_blank" class="underline">Wikimedia Commons</a></p>
                        </div>
                         <div>
                            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Brahma.jpg/800px-Brahma.jpg" alt="Lord Brahma" class="w-full h-auto object-cover aspect-square rounded-lg">
