                <!-- Definitions View -->
                <section id="defining-divinity-view" class="hidden">
                     <div class="text-center max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-8">
                        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Defining Divinity</h2>
                        <p class="text-md text-secondary-text">The quest for godhood is defined by the very words used to describe it. This section explores the key terms for divine beings across different traditions, revealing how the meaning of "god" itself changes dramatically depending on cultural and philosophical context.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Apotheosis / Consecratio</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Greco-Roman</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">The elevation of a mortal to divine status. In Rome, *consecratio* was the official state ceremony, often posthumous, by which an emperor was recognized as a god (*divus*). It was a political and religious act of statecraft.</p>
                        </div>
                         <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Akh</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Ancient Egypt</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">An *Akh* is a transfigured, immortal spirit of light that a deceased person becomes after successfully passing the trials of the afterlife. It is an effective, divine state of being, not just a ghost, capable of interacting with both gods and mortals.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Theosis / Divinization</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Christian Mysticism</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">Literally "divinization," *theosis* is the process of becoming like God through grace. The individual does not become a new god in essence (*ousia*), but becomes permeated by God's divine energies (*energeia*), achieving a participatory union.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Henosis</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Neoplatonic Theurgy</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">*Henosis* means "union" or "oneness." In Theurgy, it is the ultimate goal of the soul's ascent: a mystical union with The One, the ultimate, transcendent source of all reality. It represents the collapse of subject-object duality.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Xian</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Taoist Alchemy</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">A *Xian* is a Taoist Immortal or Transcendent. It is not a god in the Western sense, but a human who, through internal alchemy, has refined their essence, energy, and spirit to create an immortal spiritual body that transcends the cycle of death and returns to the Tao.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Elohim / Mal'akh</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Ancient Israelite Mysticism</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">*Elohim* is a plural term for God or divine beings (the Divine Council). A *Mal'akh* ("angel" or messenger) is one such being. Human mystics like Enoch did not become God, but were "translated" or transformed to join this heavenly assembly, taking on an angel-like nature.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Moksha</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Hinduism</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">*Moksha* signifies liberation from *samsara*, the cycle of rebirth. It is achieved through self-knowledge, realizing the identity between the individual soul (*Atman*) and the ultimate reality (Brahman), thus escaping the chains of karma.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Nirvana</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Buddhism</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">*Nirvana* means "to extinguish." It is the cessation of suffering (*dukkha*) and the cycle of rebirth, achieved by extinguishing the fires of greed, hatred, and ignorance through the realization that there is no permanent, independent self (*anatman*).</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="content-card p-4 rounded-lg">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Fana / Baqa</h4>
                            <p><strong>Tradition:</strong> Sufism (Islamic Mysticism)</p>
                            <p class="mt-2">*Fana* ("annihilation") is the mystical process of dissolving the ego-self (*nafs*) in the presence of God. This is followed by *baqa* ("subsistence"), a state of abiding in and through God, with one's will perfectly aligned with the Divine.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

