                                <p class="mb-2">The hero of the world's first epic, Gilgamesh, is "two-thirds god, one-third man." His quest for physical immortality fails, teaching a profound lesson: true transcendence comes not from escaping death, but from creating an enduring legacy. Gilgamesh finds his immortality in the great walls of Uruk he built, a civilizational achievement that will outlast him. The epic establishes a powerful theme of achieving immortality through lasting works rather than divine status.</p>
